PROFESSOR: Good afternoon.

00:00:24.000 --> 00:00:27.440
Welcome to April fool's day.

00:00:27.440 --> 00:00:32.409
But we'll be serious
about atomic physics.

00:00:32.409 --> 00:00:34.540
I hope you enjoyed
your spring break.

00:00:34.540 --> 00:00:35.380
At least I did.

00:00:35.380 --> 00:00:39.530
It's just a little
bit change of pace.

00:00:39.530 --> 00:00:44.410
So let me remind you what
we have been discussing.

00:00:44.410 --> 00:00:47.550
We have been talking
about interactions

00:00:47.550 --> 00:00:49.930
between neutral atoms.

00:00:49.930 --> 00:00:55.320
And that can be trivial
and very profound.

00:00:55.320 --> 00:01:00.360
Trivial because you've heard
about van der Waal's forces.

00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:03.060
Polarization forces
between neutral atoms.

00:01:03.060 --> 00:01:05.519
And if you describe
them phenomenologically,

00:01:05.519 --> 00:01:08.730
you just have 1 over r to
the 6 or whatever power

00:01:08.730 --> 00:01:10.740
of an interaction.

00:01:10.740 --> 00:01:13.980
On the other hand, if
you take the position

00:01:13.980 --> 00:01:17.780
that everything which happens
between neutral objects

00:01:17.780 --> 00:01:25.240
has to be mediated, has to be
created by the photon field,

00:01:25.240 --> 00:01:30.030
then it becomes a question of
the vacuum, the vacuum which

00:01:30.030 --> 00:01:32.350
surrounds the two neutral atoms.

00:01:32.350 --> 00:01:35.800
And I've tried in this
chapter to show you

00:01:35.800 --> 00:01:40.298
both sides, to similar or
the same physics from two

00:01:40.298 --> 00:01:41.256
different perspectives.

00:01:43.850 --> 00:01:46.540
We talked mainly about the
van der Waal's interaction

00:01:46.540 --> 00:01:49.590
between two neutral atoms.

00:01:49.590 --> 00:01:53.890
I don't want one to-- we
pretty much finished it,

00:01:53.890 --> 00:01:55.530
so I just give
you a bird's view.

00:01:55.530 --> 00:01:57.640
I don't really repeat
a lot of things.

00:01:57.640 --> 00:02:01.910
Because today we want to
talk about the forces which

00:02:01.910 --> 00:02:05.950
happen between neutral atoms in
metal plates and then two metal

00:02:05.950 --> 00:02:08.639
plates, which is
the Casimir force.

00:02:08.639 --> 00:02:13.720
But just to remind
you that we showed

00:02:13.720 --> 00:02:17.450
that the forces
between neutral objects

00:02:17.450 --> 00:02:22.150
are actually created by
quantum fluctuations.

00:02:22.150 --> 00:02:25.580
Classical objects would not
create fluctuating dipole

00:02:25.580 --> 00:02:28.540
moments, would
therefore not create--

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:32.060
would not give rise to any
force between neutral atoms.

00:02:32.060 --> 00:02:37.340
And I showed you that
there are two aspects where

00:02:37.340 --> 00:02:42.380
quantum physics comes in,
namely through the fluctuations

00:02:42.380 --> 00:02:48.070
or the zero point motion of
the atoms as oscillators.

00:02:48.070 --> 00:02:50.870
And we even had a
circuit model for that.

00:02:53.530 --> 00:02:56.700
But then I also said
that, well, assume

00:02:56.700 --> 00:02:58.750
that you have two
neutral atoms and you

00:02:58.750 --> 00:03:01.080
have the vacuum
fluctuations of the field.

00:03:01.080 --> 00:03:04.200
This vacuum
fluctuation is driving

00:03:04.200 --> 00:03:08.210
coordinated synchronized dipole
moments between the two atoms,

00:03:08.210 --> 00:03:10.640
and then the two atoms
can attract each other.

00:03:10.640 --> 00:03:13.620
So we have seen the dual role
which quantum physics plays

00:03:13.620 --> 00:03:16.820
here in terms of
quantum fluctuations

00:03:16.820 --> 00:03:20.550
of the atomic
oscillators and quantum

00:03:20.550 --> 00:03:23.150
fluctuation of the
electromagnetic field, which

00:03:23.150 --> 00:03:25.880
is another harmonic oscillator.

00:03:25.880 --> 00:03:30.790
And at least when I use
very simple pictures,

00:03:30.790 --> 00:03:34.360
it seemed that the 1 over
r to the six potential,

00:03:34.360 --> 00:03:37.560
the standard van der Waal's
potential at short range,

00:03:37.560 --> 00:03:43.000
comes from the vacuum-- from the
fluctuations of the oscillator.

00:03:43.000 --> 00:03:45.540
I didn't do the derivation,
but the simplest derivation

00:03:45.540 --> 00:03:50.635
for the long range Casimir
Polder retarded potential,

00:03:50.635 --> 00:03:54.150
1 over r to the 7, focused
on the fluctuations

00:03:54.150 --> 00:03:56.620
of the electromagnetic field.

00:03:56.620 --> 00:03:58.090
So these were some
preliminaries.

00:04:01.430 --> 00:04:04.960
Then I thought I want to show
you the power of diagrams

00:04:04.960 --> 00:04:09.900
by showing to you that there are
two different kinds of diagrams

00:04:09.900 --> 00:04:13.620
dominant at short range
and at long range.

00:04:13.620 --> 00:04:18.959
And with that we realize
diagrammatically that, because

00:04:18.959 --> 00:04:22.555
of the nature of virtual photons
which are exchanged by the two

00:04:22.555 --> 00:04:25.640
neutral atoms, there is
a change in power law.

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:29.705
The power-- the inverse power
of the distance between the two

00:04:29.705 --> 00:04:33.250
neutral atoms is one
higher at long range.

00:04:33.250 --> 00:04:37.250
And long range meant-- that also
became clear diagrammatically.

00:04:37.250 --> 00:04:45.150
Long range means the distance
is longer than the wavelengths

00:04:45.150 --> 00:04:46.819
of the resonant
radiation for the atom.

00:05:01.010 --> 00:05:02.070
Any questions about that?

00:05:06.750 --> 00:05:17.140
So the goal for the first hour
today is to go from two atoms

00:05:17.140 --> 00:05:20.830
to many, many atoms, which
then form a metal plate,

00:05:20.830 --> 00:05:23.970
and make the transition from
forces between neutral atoms

00:05:23.970 --> 00:05:26.280
to forces between two
metal plates, which

00:05:26.280 --> 00:05:28.250
is the famous Casimir force.

00:05:28.250 --> 00:05:32.020
And I want you to sort of
hold the thought about what

00:05:32.020 --> 00:05:34.150
is really the
quantum aspect here?

00:05:34.150 --> 00:05:36.390
Is it the vacuum?

00:05:36.390 --> 00:05:38.230
Is it the zero
point fluctuations

00:05:38.230 --> 00:05:39.510
of the electromagnetic field?

00:05:44.020 --> 00:05:47.700
Or are the atoms the
zero point fluctuations

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:50.750
of the atomic oscillators
responsible for those forces?

00:05:50.750 --> 00:05:54.110
So we'll come back to it after
we have discussed the Casimir

00:05:54.110 --> 00:05:56.374
interaction between
two neutral plates.

00:06:12.310 --> 00:06:16.410
So maybe one highlight for you
today is that maybe in an hour

00:06:16.410 --> 00:06:19.430
you have should at least
have an expert opinion

00:06:19.430 --> 00:06:24.420
whether zero point fluctuations
of the electromagnetic field

00:06:24.420 --> 00:06:29.660
are real or just a convenient
way to describe some physics.

00:06:29.660 --> 00:06:31.980
But let's get there.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:37.590
So the way how I want to
make the transition from two

00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:40.100
neutral atoms to
two metal plates

00:06:40.100 --> 00:06:47.340
is by reminding you that the
potential was proportional

00:06:47.340 --> 00:06:53.590
at long range to 1 over R to the
6, at short range at 1 over R

00:06:53.590 --> 00:06:54.700
to the 6.

00:07:02.450 --> 00:07:05.770
And if you had the model that
the long range interaction

00:07:05.770 --> 00:07:09.390
comes, because the
vacuum fluctuations drive

00:07:09.390 --> 00:07:14.240
dipole moments in the
two atoms, then we

00:07:14.240 --> 00:07:16.640
know that the potential
is proportional

00:07:16.640 --> 00:07:19.039
to the polarizability
of atom one times

00:07:19.039 --> 00:07:20.330
the polarizability of atom two.

00:07:24.290 --> 00:07:29.270
So let's now extend
that to the interaction

00:07:29.270 --> 00:07:34.090
between an atom and a wall.

00:07:34.090 --> 00:07:42.850
Well since I don't
know-- at least not

00:07:42.850 --> 00:07:46.900
yet-- how to describe the wall.

00:07:46.900 --> 00:07:48.830
I take the position
that, well, we

00:07:48.830 --> 00:07:51.020
have an atom come
close to a wall,

00:07:51.020 --> 00:08:02.490
but now I extend the wall
to a sphere of radius z.

00:08:02.490 --> 00:08:06.930
And it's not obvious that if an
atom interacts with the wall,

00:08:06.930 --> 00:08:09.650
if the wall were flat,
it is of course this part

00:08:09.650 --> 00:08:11.480
of the wall which
is most important.

00:08:11.480 --> 00:08:13.910
So we should actually get
a quantitative or semi

00:08:13.910 --> 00:08:18.180
quantitative result out of that.

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:23.770
But now I can use a nice
result from electrostatics,

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:31.920
which I also discuss in 8421,
in the [? MO1 ?] course, namely

00:08:31.920 --> 00:08:40.683
when we have a conducting
sphere of radius c.

00:08:40.683 --> 00:08:47.410
Do you know what the
polarizability of a sphere is?

00:08:47.410 --> 00:08:49.350
You must have also
had this problem

00:08:49.350 --> 00:08:51.700
in classical electrodynamics.

00:08:51.700 --> 00:08:53.430
You apply an electric field.

00:08:53.430 --> 00:08:57.070
You calculate with the boundary
condition of the sphere

00:08:57.070 --> 00:08:58.700
some spherical
harmonic function.

00:08:58.700 --> 00:09:00.740
You calculate what
the dipole moment is,

00:09:00.740 --> 00:09:02.750
and you find the
proportionality constant.

00:09:02.750 --> 00:09:05.960
AUDIENCE: It's like z
squared or [INAUDIBLE].

00:09:05.960 --> 00:09:06.790
PROFESSOR: Yes.

00:09:06.790 --> 00:09:11.470
The one thing I want is that
it's proportional to z cube.

00:09:11.470 --> 00:09:13.940
It's the volume of the sphere.

00:09:13.940 --> 00:09:17.040
And the reason why I discuss
that in atomic physics

00:09:17.040 --> 00:09:20.040
is when we talk about
the dipole moment

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:23.170
at the polarizability
of the hydrogen atom,

00:09:23.170 --> 00:09:26.460
we find that the polarizability
of the hydrogen atom

00:09:26.460 --> 00:09:28.926
is the pole radius cube.

00:09:28.926 --> 00:09:31.880
So it seems that when it
comes to electric fields

00:09:31.880 --> 00:09:37.920
and polarizability, an atom, a
hydrogen atom behaves exactly

00:09:37.920 --> 00:09:40.990
like a conducting sphere,
and the size of the sphere

00:09:40.990 --> 00:09:42.285
is now the size of the atom.

00:09:48.260 --> 00:09:59.315
But that means now that the
long range potential will now

00:09:59.315 --> 00:10:01.670
be proportional the
polarizability of the atom.

00:10:04.190 --> 00:10:09.550
And we lose three
powers in the power law,

00:10:09.550 --> 00:10:12.090
because we have
three powers of z

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:13.830
in the polarizability
of the sphere.

00:10:18.880 --> 00:10:23.220
OK, if that worked
so well once, we

00:10:23.220 --> 00:10:27.190
can now use that at
least as a bridge

00:10:27.190 --> 00:10:30.360
to discuss what happens when
we have two metal walls.

00:10:33.780 --> 00:10:41.510
Well, we can now say
we have two spheres,

00:10:41.510 --> 00:10:48.000
and the polarizability
of each sphere

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.030
is proportional to z cubed.

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:56.520
Well when we have
two walls, we want

00:10:56.520 --> 00:10:59.260
to use the potential per area.

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:06.950
So what we had is we
had 1 over R to the 7.

00:11:06.950 --> 00:11:10.920
We lose three powers of R
or z, because of one sphere.

00:11:10.920 --> 00:11:14.760
Another three powers of the
other sphere, so it's 1 over z.

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:20.190
But when we normalize by area,
it becomes 1 over z squared.

00:11:20.190 --> 00:11:25.330
And now we find that the
potential is 1 over c cubed.

00:11:25.330 --> 00:11:28.300
And at least with it
I have-- I wouldn't

00:11:28.300 --> 00:11:32.550
say derived, but motivated
for you the famous Casimir

00:11:32.550 --> 00:11:37.670
potential, which
is 1 over c cubed.

00:11:37.670 --> 00:11:40.740
And I want to give you an
exact derivation of the Casimir

00:11:40.740 --> 00:11:45.150
potential in the
next few minutes.

00:11:45.150 --> 00:11:48.420
But before I do that-- yes?

00:11:48.420 --> 00:11:51.950
AUDIENCE: Why did you
choose the spheres to be

00:11:51.950 --> 00:11:54.664
the same size as the
distance between them.

00:11:54.664 --> 00:11:55.590
That seems kind of--

00:11:55.590 --> 00:11:56.965
PROFESSOR: It's
all just a trick.

00:11:56.965 --> 00:11:58.945
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:58.945 --> 00:12:06.260
You know what would happen
is-- let me just go back here.

00:12:06.260 --> 00:12:08.760
If I would choose
this sphere smaller,

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:11.330
I would not have given the
atom the whole exposure.

00:12:11.330 --> 00:12:13.590
I have to make it
at least larger

00:12:13.590 --> 00:12:16.870
than c to make sure that
the curvature of the sphere

00:12:16.870 --> 00:12:19.330
doesn't dominate and
what the atom sees

00:12:19.330 --> 00:12:23.380
is it sees there is a wall.

00:12:23.380 --> 00:12:28.010
But then you can see when I
make this sphere larger than c,

00:12:28.010 --> 00:12:30.810
then I delocalize
the dipole moment.

00:12:30.810 --> 00:12:35.100
And the bigger sphere
has a big polarizability,

00:12:35.100 --> 00:12:37.040
but the atom which is
so close to the sphere

00:12:37.040 --> 00:12:38.600
doesn't care about it.

00:12:38.600 --> 00:12:40.640
So you would say
the right choice

00:12:40.640 --> 00:12:44.350
is just when you think either
picture gets corrupted.

00:12:44.350 --> 00:12:46.900
But that's often what it is.

00:12:46.900 --> 00:12:49.530
So if you think about
it, it's the only choice.

00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:53.547
Both other choices would
lead to an unphysical result,

00:12:53.547 --> 00:12:55.130
and you would
immediately realize why.

00:12:55.130 --> 00:12:59.260
In one case it's the curvature,
and the other case you're not

00:12:59.260 --> 00:13:01.760
really sampling the
dipole of the sphere

00:13:01.760 --> 00:13:06.980
because you want to
do a dipole field,

00:13:06.980 --> 00:13:12.730
and if you have a dipole of size
z, the field with the dipole

00:13:12.730 --> 00:13:15.990
starts to be an approximation
if you go distance z away.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:21.678
Other questions?

00:13:21.678 --> 00:13:23.160
Yes?

00:13:23.160 --> 00:13:26.618
AUDIENCE: Can you explain where
the first term [INAUDIBLE]

00:13:26.618 --> 00:13:29.582
z to the [INAUDIBLE] come from?

00:13:32.145 --> 00:13:33.020
PROFESSOR: We had it.

00:13:36.720 --> 00:13:39.380
Last class we had the
result that the Casimir--

00:13:39.380 --> 00:13:42.720
that the van der Waal's--
the retarded van der

00:13:42.720 --> 00:13:45.490
Waal's potential is
1 over R to the 7.

00:13:45.490 --> 00:13:47.680
But with the physical
picture in mind

00:13:47.680 --> 00:13:50.700
that the van der Waal's
potential at long range, which

00:13:50.700 --> 00:13:54.680
is 1 over R to the 7 comes
because a vacuum fluctuation

00:13:54.680 --> 00:13:59.070
drive to dipoles, and the two
dipoles attract each other.

00:13:59.070 --> 00:14:02.640
When each dipole is alpha
1 times a vacuum field,

00:14:02.640 --> 00:14:05.260
the other one is alpha
2 times a vacuum field.

00:14:05.260 --> 00:14:10.270
But now for this sphere,
alpha is z cubed.

00:14:10.270 --> 00:14:12.680
So therefore three
powers in the denominator

00:14:12.680 --> 00:14:15.400
cancel, and I get z to the 4.

00:14:15.400 --> 00:14:18.550
So you can say the
alpha 2, I absorbed--

00:14:18.550 --> 00:14:22.350
I used the kind of result
that alpha 2 is z cubed,

00:14:22.350 --> 00:14:25.130
and then the alpha 2
cancelled with three powers

00:14:25.130 --> 00:14:27.175
of the distance in
the denominator.

00:14:30.290 --> 00:14:32.950
Other questions?

00:14:32.950 --> 00:14:34.570
I have a question for you now.

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:38.780
If you have two metal plates,
what about short range and long

00:14:38.780 --> 00:14:41.340
range?

00:14:41.340 --> 00:14:44.320
We expect something
under the rock.

00:14:44.320 --> 00:14:48.970
If we assume a metal
plate, what is the vessel--

00:14:48.970 --> 00:14:53.000
we had the distinction between
long range and short range,

00:14:53.000 --> 00:14:55.320
which came from the
resonant radiation

00:14:55.320 --> 00:14:57.860
from the resonant
excitation of the atom.

00:14:57.860 --> 00:15:00.075
And when we are closer
than the wave lengths,

00:15:00.075 --> 00:15:01.700
we're in short range,
if you're further

00:15:01.700 --> 00:15:04.530
than the wavelengths of
the resonant transition,

00:15:04.530 --> 00:15:07.970
we're in long range.

00:15:07.970 --> 00:15:10.480
Between an atom and a
plate, well, we still

00:15:10.480 --> 00:15:12.220
have the resonance of the atom.

00:15:12.220 --> 00:15:16.740
But what happens when
we have two plates?

00:15:16.740 --> 00:15:20.230
There's clearly no
resonance, so therefore there

00:15:20.230 --> 00:15:23.910
is only one power
law, 1 over z cubed.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:27.660
But I want you to sort of
think about it for a moment

00:15:27.660 --> 00:15:31.120
whether this is now--
whether everything

00:15:31.120 --> 00:15:33.350
is long range or
everything is short range.

00:15:33.350 --> 00:15:38.870
In other words, you say
effective resonant radiation,

00:15:38.870 --> 00:15:41.730
you say effective wavelengths
of the plate lambda

00:15:41.730 --> 00:15:43.490
equals 0 or lambda
equals infinity.

00:15:54.205 --> 00:15:54.705
Any opinion?

00:16:02.505 --> 00:16:04.606
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]
ability, so it

00:16:04.606 --> 00:16:06.342
must be infinite [INAUDIBLE].

00:16:19.238 --> 00:16:22.875
Take the two metal
plates, the vacuum energy

00:16:22.875 --> 00:16:24.528
between those
plates, and compare

00:16:24.528 --> 00:16:29.158
it to vacuum energy at
the same volume free space

00:16:29.158 --> 00:16:32.630
and subtract the [INAUDIBLE]
energy difference.

00:16:32.630 --> 00:16:37.900
And high frequency components
cancel out, so you have the--

00:16:37.900 --> 00:16:43.730
PROFESSOR: OK, we'll actually
do exactly what you suggest,

00:16:43.730 --> 00:16:48.210
to compare vacuum energies,
in the next few minutes.

00:16:48.210 --> 00:16:50.080
It's not quite
obvious, but I want

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:53.660
to tell you now we
have made-- by assuming

00:16:53.660 --> 00:16:56.180
the metallic boundary
condition, by assuming

00:16:56.180 --> 00:16:59.050
that we have idealized
metal plates which fulfill

00:16:59.050 --> 00:17:02.200
the boundary condition
that the electric field is

00:17:02.200 --> 00:17:04.839
0 at the surface.

00:17:04.839 --> 00:17:07.420
The parallel component of the
[INAUDIBLE] at the surface.

00:17:07.420 --> 00:17:10.859
We've made an assumption here,
and the assumption is actually

00:17:10.859 --> 00:17:18.980
that the resonant
wavelengths goes to 0,

00:17:18.980 --> 00:17:23.280
and resonance frequency
goes to infinity.

00:17:23.280 --> 00:17:28.010
And the power law we obtain
is actually the long distance

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:31.380
power law so to speak,
and for two metal plates,

00:17:31.380 --> 00:17:34.510
there is no short distance.

00:17:34.510 --> 00:17:37.410
I'm not sure if I can give
you a simple explanation

00:17:37.410 --> 00:17:42.010
because the boundary condition
is so idealized that you don't

00:17:42.010 --> 00:17:45.372
recognize, you don't smell
any atomic resonance anymore.

00:17:45.372 --> 00:17:46.830
But maybe the one
