00:38:18.860 --> 00:38:20.610
have really worked
very, very hard on it.

00:38:20.610 --> 00:38:24.190
It seems for idealized boundary
condition you can do it easily,

00:38:24.190 --> 00:38:26.020
but it has been
clearly a challenge

00:38:26.020 --> 00:38:28.170
to mathematical physics.

00:38:28.170 --> 00:38:31.080
And I'm not even sure if it has
been solved in all generality

00:38:31.080 --> 00:38:34.110
or only in special
examples to extend that

00:38:34.110 --> 00:38:37.410
to every type of surfaces.

00:38:37.410 --> 00:38:41.260
But we can, for instance, assume
if you have a conductor, which

00:38:41.260 --> 00:38:46.780
is not-- conductor which has
not infinite conductance,

00:38:46.780 --> 00:38:50.350
0 resistivity, then
the electric field

00:38:50.350 --> 00:38:52.790
can penetrate a little
bit into the conductor.

00:38:52.790 --> 00:38:55.180
And if the electric
field penetrates into it,

00:38:55.180 --> 00:38:58.150
it changes the
frequency of the mode.

00:38:58.150 --> 00:39:01.377
So it's clear that the boundary
conditions have an effect here.

00:39:13.570 --> 00:39:15.670
But let's now have
some discussion.

00:39:22.790 --> 00:39:28.670
We had focused before on
the force between two atoms.

00:39:28.670 --> 00:39:33.370
And if we use a microscopic
model for the metal plates,

00:39:33.370 --> 00:39:39.170
it should be, it must be
possible to obtain the Casimir

00:39:39.170 --> 00:39:43.770
potential by just summing up
all the forces between atoms.

00:39:43.770 --> 00:39:46.430
Because ultimately if
you have no metal plates,

00:39:46.430 --> 00:39:47.560
you don't have any force.

00:39:50.510 --> 00:39:53.950
Where s-- in the
