namely if we-- here we

00:44:40.660 --> 00:44:41.550
have atoms.

00:44:41.550 --> 00:44:44.100
Here we have a metalized
boundary condition.

00:44:44.100 --> 00:44:48.990
So maybe let's just talk
for one minute about it.

00:44:48.990 --> 00:44:52.940
What kind of assumptions
do we make about atoms

00:44:52.940 --> 00:44:55.900
when we replace them by a
metallic boundary condition?

00:45:00.680 --> 00:45:02.770
From the whole derivation
of the Casimir force

00:45:02.770 --> 00:45:08.480
it's not obvious that there
are no atomic properties which

00:45:08.480 --> 00:45:13.090
have entered the calculation
of the Casimir potential.

00:45:17.350 --> 00:45:21.350
What Bob Jaffe argues in
this paper-- and again,

00:45:21.350 --> 00:45:22.580
it's wonderful reading.

00:45:22.580 --> 00:45:25.470
I really recommend Just if you
want to enjoy some physics,

00:45:25.470 --> 00:45:29.000
open up the document and read
the first and the last page.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:33.160
The Casimir force from an
idealized boundary condition

00:45:33.160 --> 00:45:36.540
is completely independent
of atomic properties.

00:45:36.540 --> 00:45:41.290
So therefore, it must be
a limit where-- well, we

00:45:41.290 --> 00:45:43.560
talked about the
resonant wavelengths,

00:45:43.560 --> 00:45:46.950
but we can also talk about
the fine structure constant,

00:45:46.950 --> 00:45:52.140
because the fine structure
constant in a hydrogenic model

00:45:52.140 --> 00:45:56.300
provides what that resident
transitions in hydrogen are.

00:45:56.300 --> 00:45:58.510
So you can argue if
something is completely

00:45:58.510 --> 00:46:00.760
independent of
atomic properties,

00:46:00.760 --> 00:46:05.310
somehow by sweeping things
under the rug we must have set

00:46:05.310 --> 00:46:08.400
alpha to either
zero or infinite.

00:46:08.400 --> 00:46:10.340
Because if it is
set to any value,

00:46:10.340 --> 00:46:13.370
it would correspond to some
version of the hydrogen

00:46:13.370 --> 00:46:15.970
atom which has a
resonant radiation.

00:46:15.970 --> 00:46:18.340
So the question is,
is alpha set to zero

00:46:18.340 --> 00:46:22.900
or is alpha set to infinity when
you derive the Casimir force?

00:46:22.900 --> 00:46:24.755
And I think this is
now easy to discuss,

00:46:24.755 --> 00:46:27.670
because the fine
structure constant alpha

00:46:27.670 --> 00:46:30.870
is e squared over h bar c.

00:46:30.870 --> 00:46:33.050
If you set alpha
to zero, you do it

00:46:33.050 --> 00:46:36.640
by setting the charge
of the atoms to zero,

00:46:36.640 --> 00:46:39.130
and then you have no
interaction at all.

00:46:39.130 --> 00:46:41.680
So therefore, if you
want to have the Casimir

00:46:41.680 --> 00:46:44.360
force in a limit which
is independent of atomic

00:46:44.360 --> 00:46:48.290
properties, the alpha equals
zero limit gives no force.

00:46:48.290 --> 00:46:57.160
So therefore, the
equivalence this picture,

00:46:57.160 --> 00:47:01.610
summing up over the electrons
and obtaining the Casimir force

00:47:01.610 --> 00:47:03.760
for the metallic
boundary condition,

00:47:03.760 --> 00:47:08.520
this equivalence happens
when you do this derivation

00:47:08.520 --> 00:47:11.585
and set the fine structure
constant to infinity.

00:47:17.090 --> 00:47:20.780
How big is the fine
structure constant?

00:47:20.780 --> 00:47:24.940
1 over 137.

00:47:24.940 --> 00:47:27.400
In some expansions of
